BACKGROUND: Staff recommends the board grant the renewal of the charter and special education agreement for Albert Einstein Academy Charter Middle School (Einstein Middle) for five-year terms beginning July 1, 2016, and ending June 30, 2021.

 

On March 1, 2016, the district held a public hearing to consider the level of support for the renewal of Einstein Middle.

 

Einstein Middle is one of the two charter schools operated by the nonprofit public benefit corporation, Albert Einstein Academies, pursuant to Education Code section 47604.  The table below summarizes the schools.

Einstein Middle is seeking a renewal of its charter for a five-year term beginning July 1, 2016, and ending June 30, 2021. Einstein Middle is located on a non-district site at 458 26th Street, San Diego, 92102, which falls within the San Diego High School cluster.  The table below provides an overview of Einstein Middle.

The educational program at Einstein Middle includes the following:

  • An International Baccalaureate Middle Years Program.
  • Acquisition of a second language (German or Spanish) during the middle years, broadening students' understanding of diverse cultures and world perspectives.
  • An inquiry-based education model accommodating individual learning styles utilizing small group work, learning centers, and cooperative learning.

When considering a petition for renewal, pursuant to Title 5 of the California Code of Regulations section 11966.4(b)(1), the district governing board shall consider the past performance of the school’s academics, finances, and operations in evaluating the likelihood of future success, along with future plans for improvement if any.

 

Staff has visited Einstein Middle annually. The annual site visit includes document review, classroom observations, and interviews of charter board members, teachers, administrators, financial managers, parents, and/or students. During the annual site visit, as well as throughout the year, the areas of academics, finances, and operations are monitored as part of the district’s oversight duties.

 

ACADEMICS

 

As the charter granting authority, pursuant to Education Code section 47607(a)(3)(A), the district shall consider increases in student academic achievement for all groups of students served by the charter school as the most important factor in determining whether to grant a charter renewal.

 

A charter school shall meet at least one of the following criteria before receiving a renewal:

  1. Attained its Academic Performance Index (API) growth target in the prior year or in two of the last three years both schoolwide and for all groups of pupils served by the charter school. 
  2. Ranked in deciles 4 to 10, inclusive, on the API in the prior year or in two of the last three years. 
  3. Ranked in deciles 4 to 10, inclusive, on the API for a demographically comparable school in the prior year or in two of the last three years.  
  4. The entity that granted the charter determines that the academic performance of the charter school is at least equal to the academic performance of the public schools that the charter school pupils would otherwise have been required to attend, as well as the academic performance of the schools in the school district in which the charter school is located, taking into account the composition of the pupil population that is served at the charter school.  
  5. Qualified for an alternative accountability system pursuant to Education Code section 52052(h).

Assembly Bill (AB) 484 amended Education Code sections 52052(e)(2)(F) and 52052(e)(4) to allow schools that do not have an API calculated in 2013–14 and 2014–15 to use one of the following criteria to meet legislative and/or programmatic requirements:

  1. The most recent API calculation;
  2. An average of the three most recent annual API calculations; or
  3. An alternative measures that show increases in pupil academic achievement for all groups of pupils schoolwide and among significant groups. 

The decision to use one of these criteria may be made on a program by program basis and is a local decision.

Einstein Middle submitted its Local Control Accountability Plan (LCAP) to the district by the required deadline.  The LCAP addressed the eight state priorities.  The following table provides a summary of many of the goals and measurable outcomes included in the Einstein Middle charter renewal and LCAP.

 

Table 12:  Einstein Middle—Summary of LCAP

State Priority

Goal

Measurable Outcome

1 - Basic Services

All students will have access to all courses and instructional resources and materials.

Purchase of Common Core versions of adopted curriculum, and 100 percent of students will have access to Common Core aligned curriculum and instructional materials.

2 - Implementation

All teachers will receive professional development on research-based strategies.

Students will receive instruction that is increasingly aligned to the Common Core State Standards.

3 - Parental Involvement

Increase resources and services to improve parent involvement including workshops, activities, and input opportunities.

Develop parent engagement opportunities through a variety of trainings and input opportunities.

4 – Pupil Achievement

Students will meet or exceed the expectations defined by the Common Core State Standards.

Implement Common Core aligned benchmark assessments for all students in ELA and Math.

5 – Pupil Engagement

7 – Course Access

Increase digital access for all students and staff.

Increase digital infrastructure.

6 – School Climate

Increase the resources and services to students to ensure student engagement, school connectedness, and positive school culture.

Students will have access to an increased number of counselors and/or mental health providers who will support student needs.

8 – Pupil Outcomes

Fully implement Common Core State Standards in all grade levels and areas and support student learning and teacher preparedness in content areas.

Facilitate teachers’ understanding and implementation of the Common Core State Standards, with the intent to create detailed teaching and coaching plans focusing on measures of success.

FINANCES

 

Einstein Middle offers all eligible employees to participate in the California State Teachers’ Retirement System (CalSTRS) and the California Public Employees' Retirement System (CalPERS).

 

Based on the most recent financial report submitted to the district, the school is projecting an operational surplus of $118,829 and an Ending Fund Balance (EFB) of $605,680. The projected EFB meets the district’s reserve requirement of the greater of 3 percent of expenditures or $50,000.

 

Over the past five-year term, Einstein Middle has submitted its financial reports including its independent financial audit report and payments to the district in a timely manner.

 

CONCLUSION

 

The charter renewal documents and special education agreement submitted by Einstein Middle are attached.

 

Staff recommends the board approve the renewal of the charter and special education agreement for Einstein Middle for five-year terms beginning July 1, 2016, and ending June 30, 2021.

RECOMMENDATION: Grant a two-year extension based on the limited amount of academic data available for Epiphany Prep Charter School and approve the Special Education Agreement beginning July 1, 2016, and ending June 30, 2018.

 

FISCAL IMPACT: None.

BACKGROUND: As the charter granting authority, the board has several options with respect to the renewal of Epiphany Prep Charter School (Epiphany Prep):

  1. Extend the term of the current charter for two years.
  2. Grant renewal of the charter for a five year term. 
  3. Deny renewal and adopt the findings contained within this report.

Staff recommends Option 1 for the board to grant a two-year extension based on the limited amount of academic data available for Epiphany Prep Charter School and approve the Special Education Agreement beginning July 1, 2016, and ending June 30, 2018.

 

OVERVIEW

 

On March 6, 2012, the board approved a petition to establish Epiphany Prep as a new charter school, and to operate a K-8 program, for a three-year term from July 1, 2013, to June 30, 2016.

 

On March 1, 2016, the district held a public hearing to consider the level of support for the renewal of Epiphany Prep.

 

Epiphany Prep is operated by a nonprofit public benefit corporation, Epiphany Prep School of San Diego, Inc.  The school is located on a non-district site at 6134 Benson Avenue, San Diego, 92114, which falls within the Lincoln High cluster.

 

The educational program at Epiphany Prep includes the following:

  • An eight-hour school day and extended school year.
  • Bi-literacy in dual language Spanish/English immersion classes.
  • A Social-Emotional Learning (SEL) program using evidence based counseling curriculum.

Staff has visited Epiphany Prep annually. The annual site visit includes document review, classroom observations, and interviews of charter board members, teachers, administrators, financial managers, parents, and/or students. During the annual site visit, as well as throughout the year, the areas of academics, finances, and operations are monitored as part of the district’s oversight duties. The table below provides enrollment and grade level data about Epiphany Prep.  There was no API, AYP, State Rank or Similar Schools Rank data available from the state during the three years of Epiphany Prep’s operation.

ALTERNATIVE MEASURES AND OTHER CONSIDERATIONS

 

Over the past three years, Epiphany Prep has increased in enrollment from serving 219 students to 253 students.

 

Epiphany Prep is a member of the El Dorado County Charter Special Education Local Plan Area (SELPA).  During the 2014-15 school year, Epiphany Prep enrolled 31 students with IEPs.  As of January 26, 2016, Epiphany Prep enrolled 32 students with IEPs, totaling approximately 12.6 percent of the schoolwide population.

In considering the available academic data, there are mixed results.  Epiphany Prep performed better than some schools, but not as well as others.  Based on the mixed results and the limited amount of data available, staff recommends that the board grant a two year extension to Epiphany Prep.

 

Epiphany Prep reported that its California English Language Development Test (CELDT) results reflected a 19 percent reclassification rate in 2014-15.  From its first year of operation through its second year of operation, Epiphany Prep reported a 53 percent reclassification increase.

 

Epiphany Prep submitted its Local Control Accountability Plan (LCAP) to the district by the required deadline.  The LCAP addressed the eight state priorities.  The following table provides a summary of some of the goals and measurable outcomes included in the Epiphany Prep charter renewal and LCAP.

As noted above, the board has the option to deny the renewal of Epiphany Prep’s charter by adopting the following findings.

 

FINDINGS IN SUPPORT OF NON-RENEWAL

  1. Pursuant to Education Code section 47605(b)(1) the Epiphany Prep charter petition presents an unsound educational program for the pupils to be enrolled in the school based on the lack of data demonstrating academic achievement. This finding is supported by the following information:
  1. Pursuant to Education Code sections 47605(b)(1) and 47607(a)(3)(A), the district has considered increases in student academic achievement for all groups of students served by the charter school as the most important factor in determining whether to grant the Epiphany Prep charter renewal and has determined that Epiphany Prep has not met any of the following criteria in Education Code section 47607(b):
  1. Attained its Academic Performance Index (API) growth target in the prior year or in two of the last three years both schoolwide and for all groups of pupils served by the charter school.
  2. Ranked in deciles 4 to 10, inclusive, on the API in the prior year or in two of the last three years.
  3. Ranked in deciles 4 to 10, inclusive, on the API for a demographically comparable school in the prior year or in two of the last three years.
  4. The entity that granted the charter determines that the academic performance of the charter school is at least equal to the academic performance of the public schools that the charter school pupils would otherwise have been required to attend, as well as the academic performance of the schools in the school district in which the charter school is located, taking into account the composition of the pupil population that is served at the charter school.
  5. Qualified for an alternative accountability system pursuant to Education Code section 52052(h).
  1. The district has reviewed the following information from the California Department of Education:


Assembly Bill (AB) 484 amended California Education Code sections 52052(e)(2)(F) and 52052(e)(4) to allow schools that do not have an API calculated in 2013–14 and 2014–15 to use one of the following criteria to meet legislative and/or programmatic requirements:

  • The most recent API calculation;
  • An average of the three most recent annual API calculations; or
  • Alternative measures that show increases in pupil academic achievement for all groups of pupils schoolwide and among significant groups.

The decision to use one of the above criteria may be made on a program by program basis and is a local decision.

 

Based on the limited CAASPP data, and an overall lack of data that reflects academic growth schoolwide and by subgroup, Epiphany Prep has not demonstrated sufficient increases in student academic achievement for all groups of students served by the charter school. Epiphany Prep has no API or decile ranks to satisfy the provisions of Education Code Sections 47605 and 47607, and based on the comparison data, the district is unable to determine that Epiphany Prep’s academic performance is at least equal to the academic performance of the schools that the pupils would otherwise have been required to attend.  Additionally, Epiphany Prep has not met the alternative measures criteria stated in Education Code Section 52052.

FINANCES

 

Based on the most recent financial report submitted to the district, the school is projecting an operational surplus of $160,110 and an Ending Fund Balance (EFB) of $536,443. The projected EFB meets the district’s reserve requirement of the greater of 3 percent of expenditures or $50,000.

 

Epiphany Prep submitted all required financial reports by the respective deadlines.

 

Epiphany Prep is fiscally solvent.

 

CONCLUSION

 

Staff recommends the board grant a two-year extension based on the limited amount of academic data available for Epiphany Prep Charter School and approve the Special Education Agreement for Epiphany Prep Charter School, beginning July 1, 2016, and ending June 30, 2018.

RECOMMENDATION: Approve revision of the charter of Urban Discovery Academy to add Grade 9 for 2016-17, subject to Urban Discovery Academy providing documentation demonstrating to the district by August 5, 2016, that the charter school has obtained all required City permits for utilities and operations, has functioning utility connections, and has otherwise satisfied all City requirements, including review pursuant to California Environment Quality Act (CEQA), to house 120 ninth grade students in portable classrooms on the parking lot at 1509 Broadway, San Diego, California.

 

FISCAL IMPACT: None.

 

PRIOR YEAR FISCAL IMPACT: None.

 

IMPACT TO DISTRICT STAFFING: None.

 

CONSULTATION WITH BOARD ADVISORY COMMITTEE: Not applicable.

 

BACKGROUND: Pursuant to Education Code section 47607, a material revision of the provisions of a charter petition may be made only with the approval of the authority that granted the charter.

 

Urban Discovery Academy is a charter school authorized by the district and currently serves students in Grades K-8 at 840 14th Street, San Diego, 92101, a non-district site located in the San Diego High cluster.

 

Urban Discovery Academy is requesting the district’s approval to add Grades 9-12, beginning with 120 students in Grade 9 in 2016-17, by installing portable classrooms on the parking lot located at 1509 Broadway, San Diego, 92101 (Broadway site). The Broadway site would serve as a temporary location for approximately one year, until the school secures a permanent location to serve the upper grades in later years. STAFF RECOMMENDATION

 

Three options for the board are summarized in table below:

 

Table 2: Option and Staff Recommendation

Option 1

Approve the charter revision to add Grades 9-12

  

Option 2

Approve the charter revision to add Grade 9, subject to Urban Discovery Academy providing documentation demonstrating to the district by August 5, 2016, that the charter school has obtained all required City permits for utilities and operations, has functioning utility connections, and has otherwise satisfied all City requirements, including review pursuant to CEQA, to house the students at the Broadway site. 

Staff recommends Option 2.

Option 3

Deny the charter revision

  

 

Staff recommends the board approve the charter revision to add Grade 9, which allows Urban Discovery Academy to return at a later date for a charter revision to add Grades 10-12. As part of the proposed revision, effective July 1, 2016, Urban Discovery Academy will begin independently reporting for California Longitudinal Pupil Achievement Data System (CALPADS) and implement an independent student information system to perform operational functions, including but not limited to attendance, transcripts, master schedules, reclassification, and special education. Urban Discovery Academy will continue to regularly report student enrollment data in the method requested by the district. Staff’s recommendation is based on the following:

  • The charter and supporting documents do not adequately describe the type and potential location of facilities needed to operate an educational program to serve 480 students in Grades 9-12. Urban Discovery Academy has stated the Broadway site would be temporary for approximately one year based on its projected enrollment of 120 students for 2016-17. The school would need to move to a different location to accommodate the projected enrollment of 480 students in later years. Thus, staff recommends Urban Discovery Academy return to the board at a later date to request approval for Grades 10-12.
  • Urban Discovery Academy exceeded the minimum financial reserve requirement per its fiscal year 2014-15 Unaudited Actuals Financial Report and First Interim Financial Report. Urban Discovery Academy submitted financial reports for the existing K-8 program by the required deadlines and appears fiscally sound at this time. However, as detailed below, the financial and operational plan presented by Urban Discovery Academy contains unrealistic components with regard to enrollment, revenue, and other areas for the proposed high school program.

DENIAL FINDINGS

 

In the event the board seeks to deny the charter revision, the board may adopt the following written factual findings, specific to the charter documents submitted by Urban Discovery Academy, to support a denial:

  1. Projected Enrollment: Pursuant to Education Code section 47605(b)(2), Urban Discovery Academy is demonstrably unlikely to successfully implement the program because it has presented an unrealistic financial and operational plan with regard to its projected first-year enrollment. Urban Discovery Academy projects enrolling 120 students in Grade 9 following an admissions lottery window that will occur April 8-22, 2016, for enrollment in 2016-17. This represents a very short period of time to recruit 120 students for a single grade level, particularly given the fact that the principal for the high school program has not yet been hired, the curriculum is presented as “to be developed” over the summer, and the facility cannot yet be toured. Current enrollment of Grade 8 at Urban Discovery Academy is only 27 students. Urban Discovery Academy states that interest has been expressed by two other charter schools, Museum and San Diego Cooperative, which have current Grade 8 enrollment at just 22 and 49 students, respectively. Urban Discovery Academy also refers to the possibility of “overflow” from High Tech High, however, this may include duplicated counts from Urban Discovery Academy, Museum, and San Diego Cooperative.
  1. Debt Obligations: Pursuant to Education Code section 47605(b)(2), Urban Discovery Academy is demonstrably unlikely to successfully implement the program because it has presented a strained financial and operational plan with regard to its current debt obligations. The construction of Urban Discovery Academy’s current facilities for the K-8 program at 840 14th Street was funded through the issuance of more than $13 million in bonds. While maintaining the “BB” rating for Urban Discovery’s bonds, Standard & Poor’s revised the outlook from “stable” to “negative” in December 2015.
  1. Facilities: Pursuant to Education Code section 47605(b)(2), Urban Discovery Academy is demonstrably unlikely to successfully implement the program because it has presented a vague financial and operational plan in the area of facilities. The charter and supporting documents do not adequately describe the type and potential location of facilities needed to operate an educational program for 480 students in Grades 9-12. As noted above, Urban Discovery Academy proposes to serve 120 students in Grade 9 by installing portable classrooms on a parking lot at 1509 Broadway Street on a temporary basis for 2016-17. Urban Discovery Academy’s plan does not describe the facilities for later years and additional students.
  1. Revenue Calculations: Pursuant to Education Code section 47605(b)(2), Urban Discovery Academy is demonstrably unlikely to successfully implement the program because it has presented an unrealistic financial and operational plan that includes unreasonable estimates of special education revenue. Urban Discovery Academy is a local educational agency (LEA) member of the El Dorado County Charter Special Education Local Plan Area (El Dorado SELPA). The El Dorado SELPA advises its members to use $505 per average daily attendance (ADA) for state special education funding and $120 per prior year enrollment for federal special education funding in multi-year budget projections through fiscal year 2017-18. However, for fiscal years 2016-17 through 2019-20, Urban Discovery Academy uses the higher rates of $513, $526, $541, and $554 per ADA, respectively. Urban Discovery Academy incorrectly calculated federal special education revenue based on $125 per current year ADA, rather than prior year enrollment. Additionally, SELPA administrative expenses and set aside are not taken into consideration in the multi-year budget projections. As a result, state special education revenue appears overstated a total of $166,758 and federal special education revenue appears understated a total of $16,093 for fiscal years 2016-17 through 2019-20. The net result is a $150,666 overestimate in revenue.
  1. Revenue Projections: Pursuant to Education Code section 47605(b)(2), Urban Discovery Academy is demonstrably unlikely to successfully implement the program because it has presented an unrealistic financial and operational plan that includes unreasonable estimates of donations and fundraising revenue. Financial projections for fiscal years 2016-17 through 2018-19 show total donations and fundraising revenue increasing each year in the amounts of $290,000, $340,000, and $375,000, respectively. This upward trajectory does not reflect the school’s actual historical record of decreasing revenue totaling $174,597 and $144,691 in fiscal years 2012-13 and 2013-14, as reported in the school’s annual independent financial audit report. Reliance on significantly increasing “soft” revenue, along with the overstated state special education revenue noted above in Finding 4, is relevant based on the draft 2016-17 LCAP projecting $30,000 in salary increases, $412,500 for additional staff for Grade 9, and other increases in expenditures.
  1. Applicable Legal Requirements: Pursuant to Education Code section 47605(b)(2), Urban Discovery Academy is demonstrably unlikely to successfully implement the program because the charter school is unfamiliar with the requirements of law that would apply to the educational program. In February 2016, Urban Discovery Academy submitted a charter revision requesting approval to locate its high school program at 525 Hawthorn Street (Hawthorn site). The district informed Urban Discovery Academy that the Hawthorn site was subject to Education Code section 17215 (school site near airport) and requested documentation demonstrating that the required notices had been submitted to the California Departments of Education and Transportation, particularly given the short timeline proposed for the program’s opening of fall 2016. Consequently, Urban Discovery Academy submitted a proposal for a different site based on the unlikelihood of complying with Education Code section 17215 in a timely manner.

RENEWAL VERSUS REVISION

 

A petition to open a new charter school can be approved by the district for up to a five-year term. Near the end of the term, a charter school applies for “renewal” of its charter to continue operating for another five-year term. Education Code section 47605 requires the review and approval process for new and renewing charter petitions to take place over two board meetings: (i) public hearing, and (ii) action to grant/deny.

 

Within a current term, a charter school may request the district’s approval to revise its existing charter pursuant to Education Code section 47607. Proposed revisions may include a change in the school’s location, reassignment of special education responsibilities, expansion of grade levels, or other significant change.

 

Material revisions of a charter are governed by the standards and criteria set forth in Education Code section 47605, and shall include a reasonably comprehensive description of any new requirement of charter schools enacted into law after the charter was originally granted or last renewed.

The School Advisory Council (SAC) is an advisory body to the charter board. The SAC currently includes two teachers, two staff members, and four parents.

 

The educational program for IDEATE High Academy includes:

  • Opportunities for applied projects and internship experiences.
  • Project-based learning in a small high school environment.
  • A focus on partnerships with business and universities, starting with the UC Extension Program at the University of California, San Diego.
  • A core approach based on the five elements of Design Thinking: empathize, define, ideate, prototype, and test.

CONCLUSION

 

Based on the documents submitted and reviewed, staff recommends the board approve the charter revision to add Grade 9, subject to Urban Discovery Academy providing documentation demonstrating to the district by August 5, 2016, that the charter school has obtained all required City permits for utilities and operations, has functioning utility connections, and has otherwise satisfied all City requirements, including review pursuant to CEQA to house 120 ninth-grade students in portable classrooms on the parking lot at 1509 Broadway, San Diego, California. Urban Discovery Academy may return at a later date for a charter revision to add Grades 10-12. As part of the proposed revision, effective July 1, 2016, Urban Discovery Academy will become independently reporting for CALPADS and implement an independent student information system to perform operational functions, including but not limited to attendance, transcripts, master schedules, reclassification, and special education. Urban Discovery Academy will continue to regularly report student enrollment data in the method requested by the district.
